segments.text: Valentine's Day.
This is Valentine's Day.
We're testing.
To continue, sir, yesterday you were talking about, or the day before yesterday, the faculty as a family here.
How did the faculty work together and share and cooperate?
First off, there were
There were a number of houses here that the people lived in.
That is, the residences, sort of thing.
Not only that, there's some of them had little houses back of them for horses.
I know several that had that.
Well, but... And some had milk cows?
Oh yeah, yeah, milk cows.
Chickens?
Yeah.
Garden?
I don't assume they did.
Yeah, you could because it was open.
There were no regulations against it.
Did they have a little place for their maid to live?
Some of them did.
Now, most of the supplementary people were Negroes.
And they came in the south side of this thing.
They came from downtown.

uh welborn way or somewhere's in there it was that away i don't know they came up through we were the last house on the on that street and uh they came by our house early in the morning and they spread out through the through the campus i'm sure that there must have been some in the northern part of the campus where they wouldn't walk that far but uh
They were Negro maids and women, and they were paid by the faculty women to take care of them.
Now, when you had wash day, which is usually Monday, you had additional help, and that was furnished lots of times by students.
Students went in there, and I know a fellow by the name of Scott, who one time or later was chief engineer for the city of Bryan.
He used to come to our house at 6 o'clock in the morning and start that iron pot out there and all of that thing, you know, and they washed his clothes.
And everybody had their clothes line in the backyard?
Yes, right.
They had a clothes line back there.
And they worked that.
Now, each one of those houses was, the departments had a home for their head of their department.
And the one we lived in for five years from 1919 to 1924 was dedicated to the etymology department.
But Dr. Bilsing was single.
So he didn't qualify.
He lived in Bryan, I think, somewhere.
Or they had some single places for him to live, like dormitories.
Did every house have a garage?
Yes, almost all of them did, even to the fact that it was the
as I said, a barn.
And it depended on how much they had to have.
The one across the street where the Hazes lived, it had a full-scale barn behind it with a hayloft in it.
And that was the only one down there, I remember, that was there.
They, those departments, they had all those houses scattered out, and that's where they, and each one of them had its own department, and the thing you had to do, the, well,
You had a society that was entirely different than anything you ever saw before.
Here's the head of the department.
He had a whole bunch of men under him.
And their families were there.
They had other houses.
Or they were in Bryan, or mostly in Bryan, because that's all the way you get back and forth.
There wasn't any housing.
outside when we first came here.
There was no housing outside.
There were a number of farmers out there that had homes and stuff like this.
So there were children involved.
But they came into the school system, that's the way.
But the, well, we went to church in Guyon Hall.
They had Sunday school there.
I was in the kids' small children's boys' class, and Dr. Reed was the one that took care of us.
And his house was the first house east and south of Guy Haller's house there.
But at the end of the Sunday school,
they would have church.
And at that point in time, the Corps came in.
And they marched in and sat down.
I mean, that guy in the hall would sit 2,700 people.
Did any of the Corps ever do any pranks or anything during church?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Most of them, they unbutton their things and they put a little magazine in there.
And you sit there and read.
I never went to church there, but we were not required to.
Where did you all go to church?
We didn't go to church.
Oh, you didn't go to church then?
We went to Sunday school.
Okay.
Okay.
William Sunday School was just like church.
Reverend Matthews got up there and waved his hands around like this, and we were singing and wearing those.
And so that's the way.
And he had a house that was just straight east of the, next to the Commandant's house, across the street there.
Now, the president's big house was just west of Sabisa.
Yeah, it was just west of Sabisa.
That's where he lived.
Were there any other big houses on campus?
Oh, yes.
There was a line of big houses on the other side of Quality Road.
Okay.
We called it Quality Road.
On the east side, the first one was the Hayes House.
It's a big old brick house.
I mean, it was brick with, uh, with, uh, the structure was brick, and then it was stuccoed on the outside.
And then it skipped a house.
The next house there was a wooden house, and the Templeton lived in it.
And then Templeton lived in it.
I don't know.
And then the Selby house came into being, the next one up, and it was a, a big
brick house with, uh, uh, stuff on it.
And then it, uh, Dean Pereer's house was there.
Pereer?
Yeah.
And then, uh, Dean Ball had a house.
Now, what?
I mean, Dr. Ball.
Oh, okay.
Not Dean Ball, Dr. Ball.
He was a

I never understood what he was, but he was always after, he and, I don't know whether it was Mark Steller, I don't think it was, it was somebody in the vet school, they were always after finding these skillets of small horses.
that whole, there's something around here somewhere with a whole bunch of them.
They used to be in Francis Hall.
They used to be in there.
And so that's where that, but the society that we had was that the head of the department and all of the people
They had a, they just would go visit people.
And did they?
Numbers of times when we would come out of Sunday school, and dad or mother would say, don't take your Sundays off.
We got to go, we got to go visit somebody, or we got to go to dinner with somebody.
I remember after Dr. Beltsy married, we went and
Had dinner with them.
Now, if the family was going to go eat out, was there a restaurant or a cafe?
No, there was no place to eat.
Had to go all the way to downtown Bryan, didn't they?
Well, of course, the Corps was fed in Spiegel.
And it always marched in the company front.
Did you and other family, did y'all ever eat much in Sabeasa?
Faculty didn't go there much to eat.
Not that I remember.
I was never in there for a meal.
All the time I was there, I never was in there for a meal.
But we would go.
In the afternoons, you had a whole afternoon.
You had no radio, no engagements.
The only thing you had was a picture show.
Was it okay for little boys to play out on Sunday afternoon on campus?
Oh, yeah.
Okay, so you could go play.
Oh, yeah, Dr. Dean Boulder.
His yard was a pretty good size.
There'd be about ten of us in there.
We'd have a football or we'd have a ball of some sort.
We'd play there and then all of a sudden down the road there, Dad would come along in the car and he'd signal, come on home.
That was all there was to it.
When you were growing up, do you remember any really bad weather, bad snow, bad ice, a flood, or anything like that?
There was a tornado here.
Really?
What happened?
Well, one morning, I remember it very distinctly.
I was in the office, right down here someplace,
underneath this place.
That's where the Ag and Air Building was.
It was an old wooden structure.
And it had a, behind it, it had a big, old barn.
The, what they called it, the, uh, the Regranovy Building, or the Agriculture Building, was built in 24.
So in 19, it was, it wasn't there.
That was the big old building they trained the soldiers in to drive cars.
That's what that was for.
But across the street where the engineering building is now was another wooden building.
It had a pitched roof on it and it had two sides to it and it was full
of machinery that was loaned to college for instruction by various companies.
I.C., John Deere, and other companies, and there were some odd ones in there, too.
But on the second floor of that thing, it was a big second floor, when that tornado hit that thing,
He took the roof off it, just the pitch roof, took it over the provision, and about several hundred yards, the other side of it, threw it on the ground.
I remember.
About when was this tornado?
Do you remember?
It was probably about 1922.
It was about in there somewhere.
Did it do any damage to your house where y'all were living?
The only thing it did damage to was that one building that housed all the ag engineering farm machinery.
And nobody got hurt badly?
Nobody got hurt.
The only thing it did, when it went over this old building that was behind the ag engineering, it dropped one of the
post, a very big old post, and dropped that, and it went right through the roof and hit the floor.
Ka-bam!
So that, nobody seems to know anything about that area, that thing, but it was, it turned, I can draw you pictures of it.
The roof was like this.
It was, it was, it was, regular,
Pitch roof, there's two sides here.
And then all of a sudden, when that roof went off, these sides laid down flat on each side.
And then the second floor had no support except down the middle.
And it got a hump in it.
It was like a camel.
And all that machinery slid off on the ground, and that's what broke it up.
And Dad, he told all the people in the department to stay quiet, and they did.
And after it was all over, they went over there and looked at it.
And he was upset, because that stuff was on loan to him.
And he didn't know whether he was going to pay for it or what.
So I remember he went and he had to, a couple of days later, he got through some telephone conversations with some of the people in Dallas that he had got the machinery from.
And he just said, well, I got to tuck my tail and go up there and ask them what we're going to do about this thing.
He walked into those people, they said, they just immediately said, have your botanist take them apart and list us a piece that you need and we'll send it to you.
Oh, how good, how good.
So that's what happened to that thing.
And he got a rapport with those people and he always had with them.
Later on, he became Secretary and Treasurer of Texas Airborne.
Now, when did he become a department head?
When he got here.
Oh, he was department head when he came.
There were only three men in the department.
And by the time he retired, how many were in the department, I reckon?
It was really lively.
I wouldn't know.
Was it one of the best ag engineering departments in the country?
It was the best.
We need to get, in the Ag Engineering Journal, there is a memorial to him.
We ought to get that thing.
It's printed in there.
Who do you think were some of his closest faculty friends?
Who were some of his favorite colleagues?
Oh, he got along with most everybody.
I know, but who were his closest friends?
Dean Kyle.
Dean Kyle.
Oh.
the Civil Engineering department because he was trained for three years in Ohio State.
So he got along with those people, Dr. Ritchie, and then I worked for Dr. Ritchie.
That was driving those students in the summertime.
There were several over there in Sandstead, was one of them, and there were several in the CE department that he got along with real good.
And the only one he didn't get along with was the English department.
Do you know why?
Well, yes, I do know.
See, when he was, the college came down here, I mean, the Hardware and Implement Association approached the college.
It must have been about 1924 or something like that.
And they said, we need some help to run this organization and to get to the organization.
And do you have anybody that could take that job?
And so it was offered to Dan.
And that's when he joined them.
And that's when they linked up.
Well, yeah, they linked up.
And he had a college, rented them the
Well, offices.
He had two offices in there that were, they were nothing but secretaries.
He ran the whole thing.
And he took care of everything.
And so we made friends all over the state.
Who do you think of all the presidents he served under, who was his favorite president?
A&M president.
I would say it turned to Dr. Walton.
T.O.
Walton?
Well, they lived right next door to us.
See, we were there.
We were on the end on the west side, and Walton's had the home adjacent to us.
So you were good friends before he became president?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
I mean, he was...
working for the extension service.
He ran the extension service.
Describe Dr. Walton's personality.
Oh, he was great.
He was a pretty good-sized man.
I mean, big man.
But he wasn't that imposing.
He carried himself well, and...
he'd stand there and talk to you just like you were, kids like you were.
And he could get up and talk, and that was what really got him to where he went.
Because in those days, you had to sell the college.
Sure.
And you had to get people out there that could help that.
Now, a little bit of back
history on that was that the Extension Service was formed just prior to World War I.
Dad was in Mississippi and he made an awful lot of good friends over there amongst the
Agriculture Riders.
He went to Europe.
Oh, good.
My, my.
And was sponsored by the Agriculture Riders Association.
Later, he went to Mexico, and then went down there again.
And the funny part about that was they had a
Baptist preacher that was in the group, and they were all telling him, you've got to drink beer, you've got to drink liquor, or wine, or stuff like that, or you're going to get sick.
And that old Baptist, he was our boy, and he was getting sick.
And when you were growing up, what did your parents give you as your guidelines for what you could not do?
Well, the one thing I couldn't approach, I couldn't get mad at my mother.
Okay.
What about strong language?
Could you use strong words?
Oh, I haven't.
I did a little, but not too much.
Smoking?
Drinking?
No, we didn't smoke.
Mother and Dad drank every night.
What did they drink?
They drank beer.
Now, where'd they get that during Depression years?
I mean, during the Prohibition years?
You had near beer.
Oh, okay.
You had Budweiser that only had about half a percent of it.
Yeah.
And they would let me drink that.
Okay.
We'd go down.
Mother and Dad would go downstairs in the kitchen before they went to bed, and they would sit there and drink one of the bottles of beer.
And the doctors always said that it was good for you.
That's what they said.
And they do that today.
Doctors tell me, go get a small drink before you go to bed.
In those years, did you all have an electric refrigerator or an icebox?
First, we had an icebox.
And did the Iceman come to the house?
Yes, he was an old man White.
Old man White.
A big, tall man.
His name was White.
And he was a... You drive a wagon or a car?
Or a truck?
I think he had a wagon.
But you put... You had some little stickers
No, they were just stickers.
Oh, okay.
And you put that on the back of the door, and they told him how much they were going to put in that box.
And originally, that was just one loaded from the top, and that was the ice pit, and then it had some stuff down there.
Immediately, almost immediately, Dad got a hold of a GE monitor top refrigerator.
The refrigerant in that is sulfadoxa instead of the regular refrigerants we had.
And he got one, and it was a small one.
One door, but it had the top on it.
And that was too small, and so he traded that for a double door with a 1V monitor top on it.
And that served us for years.
Describe your mother's routine.
In the 20s, when you kids were growing up, what did she do?
I don't know what time it was.
She bailed out of that thing, and the first thing she did was to go get that folder of coffee and make some coffee.
After she got that, she was a golden consumer.
But that's the worst thing that ever happened in this house.
And so it is.
And she worked hard at it, and she cooked, and then she called Luke and Charlie's.
Now that's Luke Patronella and Charlie Aubergine.
I remember that name.
They had a store on Northgate.
Mm-hmm.
And they deliver, did they have a truck or a wagon?
I don't, I don't know.
But they delivered the groceries.
I imagine it was a small truck.
Who were your mother's closest friends?
What other ladies were her?
Oh, Ms. Walton.
Ms. Walton came over there when Dr. Warren deemed us.
And daddy went to Brian and got him a room.
And Mrs. Walden came over there and asked mother what she needed and went and got it.
That's the kind of people.
And then the Hazes were across the street.
He was something that I'll have to look that up.
I never knew exactly.
But I think he was in the education department or something like that.
And then the Wheatlers who lived in that house later on, they were good neighbors.
Now, when the Depression hit the state, the nation, how did life on the campus change?
It didn't change.
Now, did the enrollment change much?
No.
Faculty didn't get laid up?
No.
The enrollment didn't change.
It kept growing.
Did they lay any faculty off?
No, because Texas has this biennial appropriation, and that was straddled in the crash.
Uh-huh.
We went up into 29 or something like that.
Probably 28 and 29 is what it was.
And they were paid good money at that time.
But then immediately following that is when the crash hit A&M.
But the students kept coming.
